-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/emea.support.illumina.com\/bulletins\/2016\/05\/library-quantification-and-quality-control-quick-reference-guide.html\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Library quantification and quality control quick reference guide<\/span><\/a><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"BF94D8EB5F574FAF844210790ABE8980","order_id":2,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Ensure that the mean fragment sizes of the replicates do not vary by >5% of each other. <\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1099976,"guid":"8D1DECE04F8711EB85CAC124E581317F","previous_id":1099972,"previous_guid":"ED655D604F8511EB85CAC124E581317F","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"DB06D79D25EB4617B2A9D525D35F3501","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Assays"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"B088CA5D3E8745F59A69CB756DFA5B6E","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">The following reagents are supplied with this product:<\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/cuj6bf8zp.png\" \/><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"11ED69FF9D764FD0B29F0E3D24C8729A","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/cuj6bf8zp.png\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1099977,"guid":"1EF71D304F8811EB85CAC124E581317F","previous_id":1099976,"previous_guid":"8D1DECE04F8711EB85CAC124E581317F","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"C5AF6BD5DC3D4C50B244366B3C60F9D5","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Assays"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"C7BAE090FCE44B75B1BDBA97A62AB14F","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/international.neb.com\/-\/media\/catalog\/application-notes\/improved-library-quantitation-for-a-broad-range-of-library-types-e7630.pdf?rev=db57da9b1f3441c6acc804112b3e5816&hash=518F61B3B10E511C7C5504A9097A7CC5\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">E7630 Product Information and Specifications<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/international.neb.com\/protocols\/2015\/05\/14\/experimental-considerations-e7630\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Experimental Considerations - NEBNext Library Quant Kit (E7630)<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/international.neb.com\/-\/media\/nebus\/files\/manuals\/manuale7630.pdf?rev=2b1381e2d4ca48cc9b418ae1786afb50&hash=39DAAE7C4C73439E66CC05CD3FF67E35\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">User Manual - NEBNext Library Quant Kit (E7630)<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/international.neb.com\/protocols\/2015\/05\/14\/nebnext-library-quant-kit-quick-protocol-e7630\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Quick Protocol - NEBNext Library Quant Kit (E7630)<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/international.neb.com\/protocols\/2015\/05\/14\/nebnext-library-quant-kit-protocol-e7630\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Detailed Protocol - NEBNext Library Quant Kit (E7630)<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/international.neb.com\/protocols\/2015\/05\/14\/data-analysis-e7630\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Data Analysis - NEBNext Library Quant Kit (E7630)<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/international.neb.com\/protocols\/2015\/05\/15\/expected-results-e7630\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Expected Results - NEBNext Library Quant Kit (E7630)<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"http:\/\/nebiocalculator.neb.com\/#!\/qPCRlibQnt\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Converting Cq values to nM stock library concentrations - NEBioCalculator<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">If using Illumina Library Prep protocols, refer to the following <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/emea.support.illumina.com\/bulletins\/2016\/05\/library-quantification-and-quality-control-quick-reference-guide.html\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Library quantification and quality control quick reference guide<\/span><\/a><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"D44B4866E1384417BC50CD862DD12A6C","order_id":2,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><span style = \":justify;\">If using a method other than qPCR to quantify your libraries, the subsequent pooling and dilution steps will be according to total molecules rather than sequenceable molecules, and these numbers may be different. This may, in turn, lead to variable representation of fragments on the flowcell. Shorter library molecules cluster more efficiently on an Illumina flowcell, so libraries with longer molecules may be underrepresented in the final counts. Moreover, sequence reads of very low quality are removed by the Illumina sequencer's software, so these clusters are not reflected in the post-filter read counts.<\/span><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><span style = \":justify;\">If one of the triplicates of a diluted library sample is an outlier (i.e. > 0.5 Cq from the other replicates), then the data from this outlier should be excluded from the data analysis.\n\n<\/span><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><span style = \":justify;\">For accurate quantitation, it is essential to have at least one library dilution that falls within the range of the DNA Standards 1\u20134. If all qPCR traces for the diluted library sample fall outside the range of the standards, then the qPCR assay should be repeated with greater (if faster than standard 1) or lower (if slower than standard 4) dilution.\n\n<\/span><span><\/span><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><span style = \":justify;\">The traces for the NTC may show unexpected amplification due to contamination of library targets, primer-dimers, or amplified products if the qPCR assays have been performed repeatedly. As long as the Cq value for the NTC is far enough away from the dynamic range of the DNA Standards (e.g. Cq of NTC should be > 30), the NTC amplification can be ignored as it will not have any effect on library quantitation. If the NTC shows faster amplification, new NEBNext Library Quant Dilution Buffer should be prepared for the next runs.<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><span style = \":justify;\">If one of the triplicates of a diluted library sample is an outlier (i.e. > 0.5 Cq from the other replicates), then the data from this outlier should be excluded from the data analysis.\n\n<\/span><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><span style = \":justify;\">For accurate quantitation, it is essential to have at least one library dilution that falls within the range of the DNA Standards 1\u20134. If all qPCR traces for the diluted library sample fall outside the range of the standards, then the qPCR assay should be repeated with greater (if faster than standard 1) or lower (if slower than standard 4) dilution.\n\n<\/span><span><\/span><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><span style = \":justify;\">The traces for the NTC may show unexpected amplification due to contamination of library targets, primer-dimers, or amplified products if the qPCR assays have been performed repeatedly. As long as the Cq value for the NTC is far enough away from the dynamic range of the DNA Standards (e.g. Cq of NTC should be > 30), the NTC amplification can be ignored as it will not have any effect on library quantitation. If the NTC shows faster amplification, new NEBNext Library Quant Dilution Buffer should be prepared for the next runs.<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\">The success of fragmentation and size selection is best confirmed using an electrophoretic instrument designed for automated and high throughput use, suitable for applications such as NGS. Unlike gel electrophoresis, the output of electropherograms provides qualitative measurements of 1. median fragment size, 2. distributions of fragments sizes within the sample alongside quantitative estimates like sample concentration. <\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\">An ideal electropherogram for bacterial whole genome sequencing (WGS) libraries should reveal a single peak\/band of desired size with no tailing and excessive broadening. Prior to the sequencing run, all WGS libraries are checked on a fragment analyser (the most popular of which are Agilent's Bioanalyzer and Tapestation instruments). The assays runs on these instruments are capable of verifying if library size distributions are as expected as well as the unwanted presence of any contaminating adapter-dimers or single-stranded material. These can be a major issue with exclusion-amplification clustering chemistry on Illumina platforms.<\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\">Alongside electropherograms, it is recommended that libraries be quantified to specifically estimate the amount of double-stranded usable library for equal representation within a pool when loaded onto the sequencer. This can be done using fluorometric dye-based quantitation using either a fluorometer (such as Qubit) or real-time quantitative PCR (qPCR). Between fluorometry and qPCR, only the latter can specifically target the adaptor-ligated amplifiable molecules by using primers complementary to the adaptor sequences. Quantifying only these viable sequencing templates gives you the best chance at normalising libraries accurately downstream.<\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\">This protocol describes methods to estimate: <\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\">A. library fragment size and concentration using both the Bioanalyzer 2100 and Tapestation 4200 workstations.<\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\">B. library and pool concentrations using an adaptor-ligating primer-based qPCR assay.<\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\">The steps described have been adapted from the technology and methods developed by Agilent Technologies and New England BioLabs (NEB).<\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>This is an open-access protocol distributed under the terms of the <\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/4.0\/legalcode\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike<\/span><\/a><span style = \":;\">.<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><a href=\"#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\"> <\/span><\/a><\/div><\/div><div style = 